{"id":"1909.12884","submitter":"Cynthia J. Olson Reichhardt","authors":"C. Reichhardt and C.J.O. Reichhardt","title":"Chiral Edge Currents for ac Driven Skyrmions in Confined Pinning\n  Geometries","comments":"15 pages, 21 figures","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. B 100, 174414 (2019)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevB.100.174414","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.mes-hall cond-mat.str-el","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We show that ac driven skyrmion lattices in a weak pinning channel confined\nby regions of strong pinning exhibit edge transport carried by skipping orbits\nwhile skyrmions in the bulk of the channel undergo localized orbits with no net\ntransport. The magnitude of the edge currents can be controlled by varying the\namplitude and frequency of the ac drive or by changing the ratio of the Magnus\nforce to the damping term. We identify a localized phase in which the orbits\nare small and edge transport is absent, an edge transport regime, and a\nfluctuating regime that appears when the ac drive is strong enough to\ndynamically disorder the skyrmion lattice. We also find that in some cases,\nmultiple rows of skyrmions participate in the transport due to a drag effect\nfrom the skyrmion-skyrmion interactions. The edge currents are robust for\nfinite disorder and should be a general feature of skyrmions interacting with\nconfined geometries or inhomogeneous disorder under an ac drive. We show that\nsimilar effects can occur for skyrmion lattices at interfaces or along domain\nboundaries for multiple coexisting skyrmion species. The edge current effect\nprovides a new method to control skyrmion motion, and we discuss the connection\nof these results with recent studies on the emergence of edge currents in\nchiral active matter systems and gyroscopic metamaterials.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 27 Sep 2019 19:34:00 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-11-20"}
