{"id":"1909.12957","submitter":"Tristan Ozuch","authors":"Tristan Ozuch","title":"Noncollapsed degeneration of Einstein 4-manifolds I","comments":"47 pages, V2: improved exposition","journal-ref":"Geom. Topol. 26 (2022) 1483-1528","doi":"10.2140/gt.2022.26.1483","report-no":null,"categories":"math.DG","license":"http://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/","abstract":"  A theorem of Anderson and Bando-Kasue-Nakajima from 1989 states that to\ncompactify the set of normalized Einstein metrics with a lower bound on the\nvolume and an upper bound on the diameter in the Gromov-Hausdorff sense, one\nhas to add singular spaces called Einstein orbifolds, and the singularities\nform as blow-downs of Ricci-flat ALE spaces. This raises some natural issues,\nin particular: can all Einstein orbifolds be Gromov-Hausdorff limits of smooth\nEinstein manifolds? Can we describe more precisely the smooth Einstein metrics\nclose to a given singular one? In this first paper, we prove that Einstein\nmanifolds sufficiently close, in the Gromov-Hausdorff sense, to an orbifold are\nactually close to a gluing of model spaces in suitable weighted H\\\"older\nspaces. The proof consists in controlling the metric in the neck regions thanks\nto the construction of optimal coordinates. This refined convergence is the\ncornerstone of our subsequent work on the degeneration of Einstein metrics or,\nequivalently, on the desingularization of Einstein orbifolds in which we show\nthat all Einstein metrics Gromov-Hausdorff close to an Einstein orbifold are\nthe result of a gluing-perturbation procedure. This procedure turns out to be\ngenerally obstructed, and this provides the first obstructions to a\nGromov-Hausdorff desingularization of Einstein orbifolds.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 27 Sep 2019 21:09:36 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Sun, 17 Oct 2021 14:10:50 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-11-09"}
